Someone came to fix the kitchen floor, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while revising Too Hot to Handle.
If I can only open this damn file. (Fucking OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm here.
And that's when it starts drilling really loudly. Great!
Her passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier all the way down makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like wood shavings, so it's justified even if it's an anti-mask. And besides, I really need to protect myself, don't I??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he's gone.
The positive side is that I finished re-reading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but there's big suspense. Good work.
Doing a find-replace on … ➡️  ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I hold on to it. The most natural-sounding dialogues are usually fragmented, especially when people let their emotions run wild.
The artisan is in the process of vacuuming, with a bit of luck, he will have finished soon.
He went out (as I hear), to cut something. So I took a look to see where he was at. It is far from finished :(
Only 7 pages left for chapter five. It's still my favorite chapter, and it's rather well-developed. Some formatting changes, and minor adjustments to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I could use a break and a cup of tea, but the handyman is still fiddling in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The handyman has left!
He told me he had done an estimate for the entire floor, but the owners were being cheap and only paid for the small damaged corner near the door. It's clearly better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
